1
00:00:03,726 --> 00:00:08,348
I'm Susan McKinley-Ross and I'm going to talk about epiphanies, design epiphanies from

2
00:00:08,408 --> 00:00:10,369
Quirkle and other games.

3
00:00:10,409 --> 00:00:13,150
The first thing I want to talk about is what is a design epiphany?

4
00:00:13,990 --> 00:00:18,852
And for me a design epiphany is that glorious, joyous moment when you're working on something

5
00:00:18,932 --> 00:00:23,253
and all of a sudden you understand a design concept that you didn't understand before.

6
00:00:24,034 --> 00:00:26,175
For me, it usually happens when I'm trying to solve a

7
00:00:26,215 --> 00:00:28,796
problem, I'm banging my head against the wall, how can I

8
00:00:28,836 --> 00:00:29,476
figure this out?

9
00:00:29,876 --> 00:00:32,457
And all of a sudden, I see it clearly and I understand

10
00:00:32,617 --> 00:00:35,739
viscerally something that I didn't understand before.

11
00:00:36,439 --> 00:00:39,360
And what I've noticed is that these design epiphanies are

12
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:40,861
applicable to future things.

13
00:00:40,941 --> 00:00:43,602
They don't just solve the problem I'm working on, but if

14
00:00:43,662 --> 00:00:46,403
I remember them, I can use them to solve future problems.

15
00:00:47,944 --> 00:00:49,565
The other thing I want to do is give you a brief

16
00:00:49,625 --> 00:00:51,125
introduction to Quirkle, because I'm going to be

17
00:00:51,145 --> 00:00:52,046
talking about it a lot.

18
00:00:52,694 --> 00:00:54,055
and you're gonna wanna know what the game is.

19
00:00:55,175 --> 00:00:57,216
It's an abstract strategy board game.

20
00:00:57,976 --> 00:01:00,217
It consists of 108 wooden tiles,

21
00:01:01,777 --> 00:01:03,217
and you use the tiles to make lines

22
00:01:03,258 --> 00:01:05,978
that are either all the same shape or all the same color.

23
00:01:09,836 --> 00:01:13,497
At the beginning of the game, the decision tree is pretty small.

24
00:01:14,078 --> 00:01:15,979
The scoring is very close to Scrabble.

25
00:01:16,299 --> 00:01:18,760
And, for instance, if you played those two orange tiles,

26
00:01:19,300 --> 00:01:22,901
you would score four points for the star line and two points for the orange line,

27
00:01:22,921 --> 00:01:23,962
so you'd get six points.

28
00:01:24,622 --> 00:01:25,662
And then the game goes on.

29
00:01:26,543 --> 00:01:29,004
The decision tree gets more interesting. There's more choices.

30
00:01:29,644 --> 00:01:31,625
For instance, if you played the two yellow tiles,

31
00:01:32,165 --> 00:01:34,026
you'd score three points for the X line.

32
00:01:34,046 --> 00:01:36,967
I think it's three points for the star line. I can't see from here.

33
00:01:37,841 --> 00:01:39,502
and add two points for the yellow line.

34
00:01:39,682 --> 00:01:40,782
So you'd get eight points.

35
00:01:41,322 --> 00:01:42,443
And then at the end of the game,

36
00:01:43,243 --> 00:01:45,384
there's some more interesting scoring opportunities

37
00:01:45,664 --> 00:01:47,164
and you can make quirkles.

38
00:01:47,385 --> 00:01:48,445
You can do this in the middle of the game,

39
00:01:48,465 --> 00:01:49,285
but it's less likely.

40
00:01:50,986 --> 00:01:54,367
So for instance, if you played that orange diamond

41
00:01:55,007 --> 00:01:56,008
on the middle bottom.

42
00:01:57,288 --> 00:01:59,550
you would make a corkle, because there's six shapes

43
00:01:59,610 --> 00:02:03,233
and six colors, and you can't have any duplicates in a line.

44
00:02:03,813 --> 00:02:05,774
For instance, you can't have two red squares

45
00:02:05,834 --> 00:02:07,515
and a red line or a square line.

46
00:02:08,576 --> 00:02:11,958
So when you finish a line of six, it's called a corkle,

47
00:02:12,259 --> 00:02:14,740
and you score 12 points, six points for the tiles,

48
00:02:14,780 --> 00:02:16,942
just like normal, and a six point bonus,

49
00:02:17,082 --> 00:02:18,663
and 12 points is a lot in corkle.

50
00:02:19,304 --> 00:02:21,165
So that's just a basic introduction to corkle,

51
00:02:21,225 --> 00:02:22,205
and it'll be coming up a lot,

52
00:02:22,226 --> 00:02:23,586
so I wanted you to know how you play it.

53
00:02:24,992 --> 00:02:28,834
The first design epiphany I want to talk about is pay attention to inspiration.

54
00:02:29,274 --> 00:02:32,276
And this is probably the first design epiphany any designer has.

55
00:02:33,516 --> 00:02:38,019
For me, I was working at a toy company, and they put out a call for toy ideas, and I was

56
00:02:38,039 --> 00:02:40,980
like, I can think of something, and I'll turn it into a toy.

57
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:42,421
I was so excited.

58
00:02:42,541 --> 00:02:44,102
I turned in 200 toy ideas.

59
00:02:45,163 --> 00:02:46,143
And it really...

60
00:02:47,421 --> 00:02:49,703
That's when I learned how exciting inspiration is

61
00:02:49,764 --> 00:02:51,746
and how much I wanted to design products.

62
00:02:52,126 --> 00:02:53,588
So I learned this very early on,

63
00:02:53,628 --> 00:02:55,910
but I've learned more about it as I've gone on.

64
00:02:56,411 --> 00:02:58,093
Because part of game design can be.

65
00:02:59,053 --> 00:03:00,814
really boring and kind of tedious.

66
00:03:01,894 --> 00:03:03,295
In the later part of game design,

67
00:03:03,655 --> 00:03:06,876
you're playing a game over and over and over again

68
00:03:06,896 --> 00:03:09,658
because you're trying to solve a little bit of a problem

69
00:03:09,798 --> 00:03:11,698
and make it smooth, completely smooth.

70
00:03:12,339 --> 00:03:15,300
And so what happens is when you have that inspiration,

71
00:03:15,700 --> 00:03:18,301
when you have that moment of, oh, this is a good idea,

72
00:03:18,341 --> 00:03:19,582
I can't think about anything else,

73
00:03:19,622 --> 00:03:21,003
I wanna try this, I wanna try that,

74
00:03:21,043 --> 00:03:23,524
I wanna get it down on paper, get it down on paper,

75
00:03:24,024 --> 00:03:26,685
work on it as soon as you can, work on that prototype,

76
00:03:26,725 --> 00:03:27,625
make it as soon as you can,

77
00:03:28,926 --> 00:03:32,849
That inspiration can carry you really far in the game design process.

78
00:03:33,209 --> 00:03:34,950
And the farther you go when you're inspired,

79
00:03:34,970 --> 00:03:38,313
the less far you have to go when it's kind of tedious and boring.

80
00:03:39,714 --> 00:03:40,474
So knowing that...

81
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:43,621
When I had the inspiration for Quirk Hole,

82
00:03:43,701 --> 00:03:45,222
I was able to get up that morning

83
00:03:45,282 --> 00:03:46,823
and make the first paper prototype.

84
00:03:47,564 --> 00:03:50,566
So my friends, Jessica Barnett and Dave Grossman,

85
00:03:51,067 --> 00:03:52,728
are both really good Scrabble players.

86
00:03:53,408 --> 00:03:54,589
I'm not a good Scrabble player,

87
00:03:54,969 --> 00:03:56,290
but they were at our house playing a game

88
00:03:56,310 --> 00:03:57,131
and I was watching them

89
00:03:57,171 --> 00:03:59,012
just for the joy of watching their game.

90
00:04:00,053 --> 00:04:02,295
And I realized what I love about Scrabble

91
00:04:02,695 --> 00:04:04,096
is when you make two words at once,

92
00:04:04,316 --> 00:04:05,878
when you're playing in two different directions.

93
00:04:07,017 --> 00:04:08,198
And this of course was happening a lot

94
00:04:08,218 --> 00:04:09,498
because they're really good Scrabble players.

95
00:04:10,139 --> 00:04:11,399
And then a couple nights later,

96
00:04:11,419 --> 00:04:15,321
I woke up in the morning and I had a vision in my dream

97
00:04:15,401 --> 00:04:17,422
of basically a finished Scrabble board.

98
00:04:17,582 --> 00:04:18,383
I mean a crickle board.

99
00:04:19,063 --> 00:04:21,344
And I saw something like this and I got up and I said,

100
00:04:21,884 --> 00:04:23,265
I'm gonna go make that right now

101
00:04:23,305 --> 00:04:24,806
because I knew the value of inspiration.

102
00:04:24,846 --> 00:04:25,706
I knew I'd seen this.

103
00:04:26,246 --> 00:04:27,987
I knew I wanted to work on it right away.

104
00:04:28,488 --> 00:04:30,789
I knew that the sooner I got it made,

105
00:04:31,029 --> 00:04:33,750
the more likely it would be like the thing that inspired me.

106
00:04:34,813 --> 00:04:36,794
So this is the very first corkle prototype.

107
00:04:37,194 --> 00:04:39,175
Obviously it changed and evolved from that.

108
00:04:39,815 --> 00:04:41,556
But that was the one I made that morning

109
00:04:41,736 --> 00:04:42,957
when I had the inspiration.

110
00:04:44,817 --> 00:04:46,978
Another game that happened,

111
00:04:47,838 --> 00:04:49,979
that moved really far along because of inspiration

112
00:04:50,239 --> 00:04:51,220
is Surplexed.

113
00:04:53,379 --> 00:04:55,841
So I was working on a game and I could not

114
00:04:55,921 --> 00:04:56,901
figure out the scoring.

115
00:04:57,402 --> 00:04:58,983
I still haven't figured out the scoring.

116
00:04:59,043 --> 00:04:59,903
It's a fun game.

117
00:05:00,604 --> 00:05:01,744
I should play it with some more people

118
00:05:01,764 --> 00:05:02,565
because it's a good game,

119
00:05:02,585 --> 00:05:04,166
but I could not figure out the scoring.

120
00:05:04,206 --> 00:05:06,067
No matter what I tried, it just didn't work.

121
00:05:07,048 --> 00:05:08,909
And so I was thinking about this and thinking about this

122
00:05:08,969 --> 00:05:09,950
and thinking about this,

123
00:05:10,650 --> 00:05:12,651
and I decided I'm gonna take a nap

124
00:05:13,372 --> 00:05:15,253
because I work at home and I get to take a nap.

125
00:05:15,753 --> 00:05:18,775
So I took a nap and I woke up and I was lying there

126
00:05:18,795 --> 00:05:20,416
in that kind of sleepy, groggy state.

127
00:05:21,775 --> 00:05:23,717
And the idea for Surplexed came to me.

128
00:05:24,558 --> 00:05:27,941
And Surplexed is really, really simple scoring.

129
00:05:28,621 --> 00:05:31,684
All you score are circles that are one solid color.

130
00:05:32,928 --> 00:05:33,308
That's it.

131
00:05:34,149 --> 00:05:35,270
The scoring is intuitive.

132
00:05:35,610 --> 00:05:37,171
And I really think my brain got sick

133
00:05:37,211 --> 00:05:38,732
of thinking of the other scoring problem

134
00:05:38,752 --> 00:05:40,093
and said, here's another game,

135
00:05:40,133 --> 00:05:41,854
just get over that scoring issue.

136
00:05:42,375 --> 00:05:43,696
So I had the idea for this,

137
00:05:43,776 --> 00:05:46,758
I got up and made the first prototype that evening,

138
00:05:47,298 --> 00:05:48,779
made it out of paper, started playing it,

139
00:05:48,839 --> 00:05:50,180
and it changed in Evolve too,

140
00:05:50,620 --> 00:05:52,482
but I got really far along in the design

141
00:05:52,542 --> 00:05:54,683
because I acted on the inspiration when I had it.

142
00:05:55,864 --> 00:05:57,465
The next design epiphany I wanna talk about

143
00:05:58,446 --> 00:06:00,548
is being stuck as part of the process.

144
00:06:01,208 --> 00:06:01,528
Darn it.

145
00:06:02,919 --> 00:06:05,263
My husband and I were working on the Quirkle app.

146
00:06:05,723 --> 00:06:06,705
We weren't developing it.

147
00:06:06,865 --> 00:06:08,688
MFV did a really nice job on it,

148
00:06:08,708 --> 00:06:10,831
but we were playing it and giving feedback.

149
00:06:11,629 --> 00:06:15,993
And I got up one morning and pulled out my iPad to start working on it, and it didn't work.

150
00:06:16,834 --> 00:06:20,838
Everything was broken. It wouldn't play. Nothing, nothing worked.

151
00:06:20,878 --> 00:06:25,823
And I was freaking out because I was like, it worked yesterday. Everything made sense yesterday.

152
00:06:25,843 --> 00:06:30,367
And my husband got up and he looked at me and he said, well, you know, it's part of the process.

153
00:06:30,507 --> 00:06:33,851
Everything breaks, and then it gets fixed, and it works again.

154
00:06:34,972 --> 00:06:40,015
And this was an epiphany for me because I'd spent most of my career working alone and

155
00:06:40,655 --> 00:06:44,918
even though many of my games broke in the middle, I hadn't realized it was part of the process.

156
00:06:45,158 --> 00:06:49,822
And when Chris said it, he had been working in the video game industry for 14 years before I

157
00:06:49,862 --> 00:06:55,065
hired him away to do board games. And when he said it and I realized whole teams of people would get

158
00:06:55,085 --> 00:07:00,008
in the situation where they got stuck and their game got broken and then it worked again.

159
00:07:00,519 --> 00:07:03,001
It really helped me be calm about what happened.

160
00:07:03,081 --> 00:07:05,903
And it actually, the next day, everything worked perfectly.

161
00:07:06,804 --> 00:07:09,246
And it's helped me in future game design since then

162
00:07:09,306 --> 00:07:11,327
to realize that it's just part of the process.

163
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:14,070
You reach a point where everything seems impossible

164
00:07:14,090 --> 00:07:18,013
and that happens and you keep going and you keep trying

165
00:07:18,193 --> 00:07:19,474
and eventually you find a solution.

166
00:07:19,894 --> 00:07:20,715
Hopefully an epiphany.

167
00:07:22,136 --> 00:07:23,257
The next one I wanna talk about.

168
00:07:24,833 --> 00:07:26,074
Add more bingos.

169
00:07:26,654 --> 00:07:29,616
So this one, we have a monthly game night

170
00:07:29,636 --> 00:07:30,657
that we've hosted since 1998,

171
00:07:31,758 --> 00:07:34,319
and we had friends over who were playing.

172
00:07:34,359 --> 00:07:37,481
They were very gracious early playtesters of Quirkle,

173
00:07:37,962 --> 00:07:39,663
and they were playing the early version there

174
00:07:39,743 --> 00:07:43,085
shown with eight shapes and eight colors

175
00:07:43,145 --> 00:07:44,466
and two of each tile.

176
00:07:45,547 --> 00:07:47,628
And my friend Andrew Kirmsey played it,

177
00:07:47,648 --> 00:07:50,090
and he said, it's a good game, it's kind of interesting,

178
00:07:50,130 --> 00:07:51,471
but it needs more bingos.

179
00:07:52,653 --> 00:07:55,014
And I just thought, oh, that's so smart.

180
00:07:55,054 --> 00:07:56,034
It needs more bingos.

181
00:07:56,474 --> 00:07:58,595
You need more minor victories.

182
00:07:58,635 --> 00:07:59,955
You need more personal victories.

183
00:07:59,995 --> 00:08:02,436
You need more moments of, oh, I made a good play.

184
00:08:03,496 --> 00:08:04,757
And so I thought about it and thought about it.

185
00:08:04,777 --> 00:08:06,797
And eventually what happened is Quirkle evolved

186
00:08:06,857 --> 00:08:09,858
into six shapes, six colors, three of each tile.

187
00:08:10,279 --> 00:08:13,540
And that definitely increases your opportunities

188
00:08:13,580 --> 00:08:15,320
for bingos, or in this case, Quirkles,

189
00:08:15,800 --> 00:08:18,161
because it was much easier to score a line of six

190
00:08:18,221 --> 00:08:19,382
than to score a line of eight.

191
00:08:19,822 --> 00:08:20,902
And there were three of each tile.

192
00:08:22,583 --> 00:08:27,206
So doing that, ever since then, I've thought about the games I've designed and tried to add more bingos to them.

193
00:08:27,286 --> 00:08:33,090
Because I've played games, and I realize that there's lots of times where there's a small victory in a game.

194
00:08:33,550 --> 00:08:36,372
You get a Yahtzee, you get a bingo in Scrabble, you get a Quirkle.

195
00:08:36,813 --> 00:08:39,995
Something like that happens, and it makes you feel good about the game.

196
00:08:40,495 --> 00:08:46,319
And you may not win the game, but at least you have that moment of victory when you get that small little goal met.

197
00:08:46,919 --> 00:08:50,362
And so I've been trying to add more bingos to my games ever since the beginning.

198
00:08:51,522 --> 00:08:53,104
This is Skipity.

199
00:08:54,426 --> 00:08:57,590
So Skipity is basically my version of Checkers,

200
00:08:57,791 --> 00:09:00,014
but in Checkers, it takes a while before you

201
00:09:00,034 --> 00:09:01,155
start to get to make jumps.

202
00:09:01,295 --> 00:09:03,598
And in this one, you're making jumps from the very first turn

203
00:09:03,718 --> 00:09:04,419
and every turn.

204
00:09:04,900 --> 00:09:07,243
There's double jumps, triple jumps, quadruple jumps.

205
00:09:07,744 --> 00:09:09,306
And each of those are a little bit of a bingo.

206
00:09:09,987 --> 00:09:12,008
And then you're trying to collect sets,

207
00:09:12,408 --> 00:09:13,648
one piece of each color.

208
00:09:14,048 --> 00:09:15,469
When you have a set, there's a bingo.

209
00:09:16,189 --> 00:09:18,270
The person with the most sets at the end of the game wins.

210
00:09:18,871 --> 00:09:20,972
And so Skippity is kind of my version of checkers

211
00:09:21,432 --> 00:09:22,372
with more bingos.

212
00:09:25,276 --> 00:09:31,098
When Quirkle won the Spiel des Jars, the German publisher asked me to come up with an expansion for Quirkle.

213
00:09:31,538 --> 00:09:34,518
And it took a really long time to figure out what that was going to be.

214
00:09:35,178 --> 00:09:38,359
This is the first expansion that came out for Quirkle, and it's a set of boards.

215
00:09:38,399 --> 00:09:40,660
They're double-sided. I'm just going to talk about one side.

216
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:46,301
So I was working on an expansion for Quirkle, and I wanted to add more bingos to Quirkle.

217
00:09:47,101 --> 00:09:50,462
And so Quirkle Select has little spaces on the board,

218
00:09:50,902 --> 00:09:53,403
and you put the little wooden star tokens on the board.

219
00:09:54,308 --> 00:09:56,930
And when you get to a spot that has a select token, you get

220
00:09:56,950 --> 00:10:00,092
to take the select token from the board and add it to your

221
00:10:00,132 --> 00:10:03,554
hand, and then on any future turn, you can spend the token

222
00:10:03,714 --> 00:10:05,815
and take a piece off the board and add it to your hand.

223
00:10:06,275 --> 00:10:09,057
So if you need a red square to finish a quirkle, you just

224
00:10:09,097 --> 00:10:09,958
take it off the board.

225
00:10:10,318 --> 00:10:12,700
So there's a bingo of when you get the select token, the

226
00:10:12,740 --> 00:10:15,421
bingo of when you use it, and usually there's more quirkles

227
00:10:15,481 --> 00:10:17,703
in a select game because there's more opportunities

228
00:10:18,483 --> 00:10:19,644
because of the select tokens.

229
00:10:20,284 --> 00:10:23,426
So those are all cases for me where adding more bingos was

230
00:10:23,466 --> 00:10:23,706
really.

231
00:10:24,450 --> 00:10:25,691
important to my game design.

232
00:10:29,034 --> 00:10:31,076
Write the rules early and often.

233
00:10:31,216 --> 00:10:32,478
Oh, I wish I'd learned this earlier.

234
00:10:32,498 --> 00:10:34,920
I was working on Quirkle Cards.

235
00:10:35,661 --> 00:10:37,562
Quirkle Cards was a tough nut for me to crack.

236
00:10:37,603 --> 00:10:40,285
I took a lot of time to figure out a fun game there.

237
00:10:41,524 --> 00:10:43,485
And what I normally do in my playtesting process

238
00:10:43,525 --> 00:10:45,385
is I play a game a lot against myself,

239
00:10:45,985 --> 00:10:48,206
and then I take it to playtesters and get their response,

240
00:10:48,686 --> 00:10:49,966
and then I go back and revise it,

241
00:10:50,526 --> 00:10:52,427
and then I take it to playtesters and get their response,

242
00:10:52,447 --> 00:10:54,147
and then I go back and revise it, and it's a lot of that,

243
00:10:54,267 --> 00:10:56,288
and I normally don't write the instructions to the end,

244
00:10:56,388 --> 00:10:58,568
because it always seemed like a waste of time to me

245
00:10:59,409 --> 00:11:00,789
to put them down when they're just gonna be

246
00:11:00,829 --> 00:11:02,649
changing, changing, changing, changing.

247
00:11:03,090 --> 00:11:05,990
So I would just give the playtesters verbal rules.

248
00:11:07,492 --> 00:11:08,972
And so I was working on Quirkle Cards,

249
00:11:09,572 --> 00:11:11,193
and I was playtesting with my husband, Chris.

250
00:11:11,633 --> 00:11:15,015
And he said, please, please, can you give me some written rules?

251
00:11:15,495 --> 00:11:16,315
And I said, why?

252
00:11:16,355 --> 00:11:18,576
And he said, I played so many different versions

253
00:11:18,636 --> 00:11:20,897
of this game, Quirkle Cards, I can't

254
00:11:20,977 --> 00:11:23,138
remember what the rules are when you tell me any more.

255
00:11:23,558 --> 00:11:25,359
Can you just write them down so I can see them?

256
00:11:25,379 --> 00:11:26,599
And I said, sure, that's no big deal.

257
00:11:27,059 --> 00:11:29,180
And I sat down to write them, and I immediately

258
00:11:29,240 --> 00:11:30,681
realized how powerful it was.

259
00:11:31,221 --> 00:11:34,062
Because as I was writing them, I was like, oh, that's

260
00:11:34,302 --> 00:11:35,603
really hard to explain.

261
00:11:36,877 --> 00:11:40,699
If it's this hard to explain in writing, it doesn't make sense for one of my games.

262
00:11:41,379 --> 00:11:42,820
It's too complex a rule.

263
00:11:43,380 --> 00:11:47,362
And I realized from that point on that when I was writing the rules early and I was writing

264
00:11:47,402 --> 00:11:52,064
them often, it helped me with the game design, it helped me figure out how to smooth things

265
00:11:52,204 --> 00:11:53,905
out and how to make the games...

266
00:11:55,805 --> 00:11:57,125
clearer from the very beginning.

267
00:11:57,205 --> 00:12:00,607
And then the other part is writing game rules is hard.

268
00:12:01,107 --> 00:12:03,969
You have to strike this balance between being very clear

269
00:12:04,449 --> 00:12:08,871
about 90% of the cases and being very legal about the 10%

270
00:12:09,231 --> 00:12:10,172
of outlier cases.

271
00:12:10,212 --> 00:12:13,033
And it's almost this balance between clear language

272
00:12:13,093 --> 00:12:15,054
and very legal language and figuring it out.

273
00:12:15,374 --> 00:12:17,195
And when I started writing my rules early

274
00:12:17,215 --> 00:12:20,416
and keeping drafts of them and writing them over and over

275
00:12:20,476 --> 00:12:22,077
in the design process, I was able to do that.

276
00:12:22,277 --> 00:12:25,742
I found that the language got better and better each time.

277
00:12:26,223 --> 00:12:30,088
When it was time to write the final rules and turn it into the publisher, it was much

278
00:12:30,168 --> 00:12:31,630
easier because I'd done all this work.

279
00:12:31,990 --> 00:12:35,856
So it helped both the game design and the final writing of the rules.

280
00:12:37,458 --> 00:12:39,040
The last epiphany I want to talk about.

281
00:12:40,135 --> 00:12:41,797
Prototypes are powerful.

282
00:12:42,878 --> 00:12:46,060
I also think of this as what you show is what you get.

283
00:12:46,841 --> 00:12:49,143
And my experience is probably a little different

284
00:12:49,163 --> 00:12:50,084
from most designers.

285
00:12:50,884 --> 00:12:53,046
Designers and publishers will both tell you

286
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:54,948
you don't have to have a perfect prototype

287
00:12:54,968 --> 00:12:56,589
when you send it in, and I think that's true.

288
00:12:57,070 --> 00:12:59,011
I think publishers are able to see a game

289
00:12:59,071 --> 00:13:01,333
and decide if it's good, whether or not the art

290
00:13:01,473 --> 00:13:02,915
and the prototype are perfect.

291
00:13:04,047 --> 00:13:08,150
But I think there's real value in when you show a publisher a prototype,

292
00:13:08,210 --> 00:13:11,133
it's as close as it can be to what you want it to be.

293
00:13:11,653 --> 00:13:15,076
And the reason is that that way, when they license it,

294
00:13:15,156 --> 00:13:17,538
they have the same idea in mind as you do.

295
00:13:18,078 --> 00:13:20,420
You're agreeing on what you want the product to be,

296
00:13:20,820 --> 00:13:22,061
and you're seeing the same thing.

297
00:13:22,742 --> 00:13:25,103
If you give them a prototype that isn't completely thought

298
00:13:25,203 --> 00:13:28,045
out and that isn't an expression of what you want,

299
00:13:28,505 --> 00:13:30,227
then they're going to start thinking of it that way.

300
00:13:30,327 --> 00:13:31,828
And they're going to take it a different direction.

301
00:13:32,308 --> 00:13:35,910
So I want to just show some examples of products that I

302
00:13:35,950 --> 00:13:39,113
submitted to publishers and how what I got back really

303
00:13:39,153 --> 00:13:40,333
reflects what I showed them.

304
00:13:42,155 --> 00:13:43,836
So this is GeoColor Cards Kit.

305
00:13:43,996 --> 00:13:45,617
It was way before coloring was cool.

306
00:13:46,237 --> 00:13:47,358
So I missed the boat on that one.

307
00:13:47,378 --> 00:13:48,239
I was too early on the boat.

308
00:13:50,727 --> 00:13:52,808
And I submitted this to a company called HearthSong,

309
00:13:52,889 --> 00:13:54,750
and one of their core values was not

310
00:13:54,810 --> 00:13:56,211
to spend money on packaging.

311
00:13:56,512 --> 00:13:58,654
They really felt it was important to spend their money

312
00:13:59,134 --> 00:14:02,197
on the product and not waste money on packaging.

313
00:14:02,237 --> 00:14:03,358
That was really important to them.

314
00:14:04,288 --> 00:14:06,008
And I submitted this coloring card kit,

315
00:14:06,508 --> 00:14:10,369
and I wanted it in a hinged pencil box

316
00:14:11,030 --> 00:14:15,391
so that it would have a use beyond just when you got it,

317
00:14:15,491 --> 00:14:17,491
and that it would feel like a real stationary set.

318
00:14:17,871 --> 00:14:19,992
And I didn't have a plain white box.

319
00:14:20,032 --> 00:14:21,372
I had a pretty purple box.

320
00:14:21,892 --> 00:14:23,633
So I sent it in a pretty purple box.

321
00:14:24,073 --> 00:14:25,973
And they got it, and they said they were going to license it.

322
00:14:26,333 --> 00:14:28,314
And they put it in a pretty purple box.

323
00:14:29,154 --> 00:14:32,097
And it's only because they saw it in a pretty purple box

324
00:14:32,357 --> 00:14:33,838
that I got a pretty purple box.

325
00:14:34,239 --> 00:14:37,121
If I had sent it in a white box, I'd have a white box.

326
00:14:37,582 --> 00:14:38,823
So that was really amazing to me.

327
00:14:38,863 --> 00:14:40,865
I realized, hey, I can trick them

328
00:14:40,905 --> 00:14:42,226
into giving me good packaging.

329
00:14:42,847 --> 00:14:43,387
And it worked.

